When I do a merge, and have a merge conflict, the code shows:

{code:java}
<<<<<<< HEAD
func(1, 4, 5, 3);
=======
func(2, 7, 1, 4);
>>>>>>> master
{code}

It would be helpful to know that the original line was:
{code:java}
func(1, 7, 5, 4);
{code}

So I could see that the first branch changed the second and forth parameters, and the second branch changed the first and third parameters.  If these are independent, then there is no actual conflict, and I can easily manually merge the line.  Otherwise, I have to research everything (and it may not otherwise be clear what has changed in which branch).  Multiply this effort if your code is more than my example.  Perhaps the original code had no call to func, and the correct merge should have two calls, with the various parameters.

I would suggest adding a 3rd block (but placed first) that shows the original code for this purpose.  In fact, I would think that this (original code) block would be the "HEAD".
